DTSA 5510 Final Project¶

Author: Tyler B.

2023 Spring 1 Semester

Project Description¶

For my unsupervised learning project, I chose to work on a clustering problem. While this class covered clustering in Week 2, I wanted to study clustering more in depth. Specifically, I wanted the chance to experiment with Gaussian Mixture Models, which is a popular clustering model that was not taught in this class. In my work as a Data Scientist, I have seen clustering problems pop up, and I would love to have a better understanding of the solutions that are available!

Data Description¶

My dataset comes from Kaggle and can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/tabular-playground-series-jul-2022/data

The problem is a classic unsupervised clustering problem. See the data description from the kaggle site below

Problem Statement¶

As the data description states, the problem at hand relates to manufacturing control data. Specifically, I will seek to cluster observations from a manufacturing process into different manufacturing control states. If this can be done, then we can deduce what control state a process is in based off the readings we are getting from the process.

Data Munging¶

Next, I will perform some data munging / transforming on the dataset. Mainly, I will standardize all of the features. This will ensure that all of the features are scaled in the same way. This is very important in clustering since most algorithms use distance based metrics. Without scaling, high mean features would have a greater impact than low mean features.

In our case, we do not need to do any data cleaning or imputation since we have no missing values. This would normally be an important step in data science work.

In [ ]:
for col in df.columns:
  df[col] = (df[col] - df[col].mean()) / df[col].std()

Model Analysis¶

Now that we have performed our EDA and munged our data, we are ready to begin building models. For the purpose of this project, we will look at 3 different models, a K-means clustering model, a K-means clustering model aided with PCA, and a Gaussian Mixture Model.

K-means Clustering¶

First, we will experiment with a K-means clustering model. I have chosen to use pyclustering over the more popular sklearn clustering, because pyclustering lets you change the distance metric for the model. This is an important hyperparameter that I would like to tune. The below code loops through 4 common distance metrics and reports the elbow score for each number of clusters from 1 to k. This will be useful in making our elbow plot.

Gaussian Mixture Model¶

We did not cover gaussian mixture models in this class, but they are powerful clustering models that can solve a variety of problems. Here is a brief description with a comparison to the k-means clustering algorithim.

Gaussian Mixture Models (GMMs), assume that each data point is generated from a mixture of Gaussian distributions. It attempts to estimate the number of data points that come from each underlying gaussian distribution. Some key differences between GMMs and K-means clustering are:

  • GMMs are much more flexible. They can detect clusters of any shape while K-means is limited to spherical clusters.
  • GMMs perform better when the clusters are not clearly seperated and defined.
  • GMMs can handle missing data, while k-means can not.
  • GMMs take into account the variance of the data, while k-means does not
  • GMMs assign a probablity for each data point for each class. This is more information than can be extracted from a k-means clustering algorithm.

All in all, GMMs are very powerful clustering models and I recommend studying them more. Here is an article that I found helpful https://vitalflux.com/gaussian-mixture-models-what-are-they-when-to-use/

For my model analysis, I will be using sklearn's Gaussian Mixture Model. Additionally, one key hyperparameter is the covariance matrix type. Similar to the k-means clustering, I will generate plots comparing all of the covariance matrix types for k = 1,10

In [ ]:
covariance_types = ['full', 'tied', 'diag', 'spherical']
bics = {}
aics = {}

for cov_type in covariance_types:
  bics[cov_type] = []
  aics[cov_type] = []
  for k in range(1, 11):
    n_clusters = k
    gm_model = GaussianMixture(n_components=n_clusters, covariance_type=cov_type, random_state=seed)
    gm_model.fit(df)
    bics[cov_type].append(gm_model.bic(df))
    aics[cov_type].append(gm_model.aic(df))

    print('cov_type = {}, K = {}, Bic = {}, Aic = {}'.format(cov_type, k, bics[cov_type][k-1], aics[cov_type][k-1]))

Again, we can see that the best model using the full covariance matrix and has k = 7. We can create a model with those options and pass it to the kaggle api.

gm_model = GaussianMixture(n_components=7, random_state=seed, covariance_type='full')
gm_model.fit(df_high_var)
cluster_labels = gm_model.predict(df_high_var)

results = pd.DataFrame()
results['Id'] = df_with_id['id']
results['Predicted'] = cluster_labels

results.to_csv('gaussian_mixture_output_feature_selection.csv', index=False)

This resulted in an accuracy score of 0.495 which is an improvement over the previous GMM model. All in all, it seems that GMM is the way to go for this problem!

Conclusion¶

For my DTSA 5510 Final Project, I attempted to solve a clustering problem from a publicly available kaggle dataset. This problem was a great chance for me to grow in my clustering abilities. In total, I experimented with:

  • K-means clustering
  • K-means clustering with PCA
  • Gaussian Mixture Models
  • Gaussian Mixture Models with only high variability features

The best performing cluster model was the last one, the GMM with only high variability features. This seems to indicate that there are a handful of features that are more important for this clustering task than the others. Additionally, the success of the GMM when compared the k-means model indicates that the clusters are not well defined and not spherical.

Overall, this was a great problem to work on, and I now feel much more skilled with clustering!

Future Work¶

If I had more time, these are some of the things that I would add to this project. These are future work ideas that would benefit this project!

  • Using the silhoutte score to compare the GMMs and k-means clustering models. In the real world, the kaggle accuracy score would not be available so the silhoutte score would help compare different model types.
  • Experimenting with Bayesian GMMs. These are GMMs that can affectively deduce k on their own.
  • Conducting more GMM experiments with different combinations of the high variability features.
